A REVELLER suffered horrific injuries when he was attacked by a brutal thug in Glasgow city centre.The 43-year-old was left with a fractured neck, broken jaw and serious damage to his eye orbits, after he was targeted.He is understood to have been on a night out when he was walking along Midland Street at around 11.45pm on Saturday.Emergency services raced to the scene after the alarm was raised.The victim was taken by ambulance to hospital, where he is receiving treatment for serious head and facial injuries.He is currently detained Glasgow Royal Infirmary and hospital staff described his condition as &quot;serious&quot;.Detective Sergeant Alister Thom, from the City Centre Police Office, is leading the investigation into the Midland street attack.He said: &quot;Police inquiries are ongoing to establish how this man came about his injuries.&quot;At this time, I would appeal to anyone who was in the Midland Street area around 11.45pm on Saturday night and may have information that will assist our investigation to come forward.&quot;Police Scotland can be contacted on 101.&quot;Meanwhile, two women were arrested in connection with an alleged stabbing incident in Glasgow city centre.Police said a 28-year-old man was taken to hospital after the incident in Union Street at around 12.15am on Saturday.A 26-year-old woman and a 30-year-old woman were arrested in connection with the incident.Police were continuing their probe after a young man was attacked in the East End of Glasgow.The 26-year-old suffered injuries to his head and face during the attack in Castlelaw Gardens, Springboig, at around 8am yesterday.Detectives are examining CCTV footage in a bid to find out more details about the incident.A Police Scotland spokeswoman said: &quot;At 8.10am, a 26-year-old man was discovered with head and face injuries after being attacked at Castlelaw Gardens.&quot;He was taken to Glasgow Royal Infirmary where he was treated for his injuries.&quot;Police are examining CCTV images to determine the circumstances of the incident.&quot;Anyone with any information is asked to contact police on 101.